"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347723","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-05","<p>My Right Hon. Friend the Secretary of State is currently considering a range of options for reviewing the BBC's Royal Charter and will make an announcement in due course.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","526 ; 527 ; 568 ; 569","2015-06-05T09:03:33.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347723/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347723/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347723/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-01","BBC: Royal Charters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, when he plans to publish his timetable for the BBC Charter renewal.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","528"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347724","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-08","<p>My Right Hon. Friend the Secretary of State has spoken with the Attorney General. They agreed that the British authorities will offer full co-operation with American and Swiss investigators, and that if any evidence of criminal wrongdoing in the UK emerges, we will fully the support the Serious Fraud Office and other relevant authorities in pursuing those involved.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-06-08T11:53:41.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347724/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347724/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347724/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-01","FIFA: Corruption","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether he has had discussions with the Attorney General regarding allegations of corruption at FIFA.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","529"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347725","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-09","<p>The Government currently has no plans to alter the restrictions on the premises which can be licensed to have fixed-odds betting terminal machines or alter the number of FOBTs allowed per betting shop. Nevertheless, the Government continues to monitor the effects of existing controls and if need be will take action if these controls are found to be insufficient.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","523","2015-06-09T10:09:02.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347725/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347725/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347725/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-01","Betting Shops: Gaming Machines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether he plans to bring forward proposals to alter the number of fixed-odds betting terminal machines allowed in each betting shop.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","530"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347726","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-08","I have regular discussions with content creators on a range of matters. The UK wants the EU to create an open, flexible digital single market with a regulatory framework that reflects the dynamic nature of the digital economy, benefits consumers and protects the interests of content creators.","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-06-08T14:48:28.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347726/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347726/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347726/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-01","Digital Technology: EU Internal Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions he has had with content creators about the European Commission's Digital Single Market proposals.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","571"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347727","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-08","<p>The Government believes that prices should be set by supply and demand in the secondary ticketing market.</p><p> </p><p>The measures set out in the Consumer Right Act 2015, which came into force on 27 May, will enable consumers to make an informed decision on the tickets they purchase.</p><p> </p><p>The Government encourages all fans to look to official primary and secondary sites, such as the 2015 Rugby World Cup’s official resale platform, for the safest and most secure method of buying tickets at face value.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-06-08T11:57:21.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347727/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347727/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347727/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-01","Tickets: Sales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps he is taking to ensure that tickets for the Rugby World Cup and Ashes cricket tests are sold at face value in the secondary ticketing market.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","572"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347728","Department for Transport","true","2015-06-08","<p>The construction of a new station at Horden is being promoted by Durham County Council and funded from the North East Local Enterprise Partnership Growth Deal. To date, no approval has been sought from the Secretary of State for its opening. The Department would expect the sponsors to work with the future Northern franchisee to develop a deliverable plan.</p><p> </p><p>The Invitation to Tender for the northern rail franchise, published in February 2015, confirmed that we would be asking bidders to replace the Pacer trains and introduce 120 new-build vehicles by January 2020. This is part of our transformation of rail travel in the north and a step in the creation of a northern powerhouse for the UK economy.</p><p> </p><p>The Government established Transport for the North (TfN) in October 2014 to formalise cooperation on transport issues in the North. The aim is for TfN to speak with one voice to Government on the transport priorities for the whole of the North. The Department is working closely with TfN and Rail North to develop and prioritise the rail options so that the first tranche is ready for consideration as part of the Government’s Rail Investment Strategy for the next rail investment period (CP6, 2019 – 2024).</p><p> </p><p><del class="ministerial">There is currently a two-hourly Northern service on the Middlesbrough-Sunderland-Newcastle route, with a couple of extra services. By December 2017, this will become an hourly service.</del></p><p><ins class="ministerial"> <p /> <p>Northern Rail provides an hourly service in each direction between Newcastle and Middlesbrough throughout the day with some additional trains at peak times with some through trains serving Hexham and Nunthorpe. Northern improved the Sunday service frequency between Newcastle and Middlesbrough in May 2015 so trains now run every hour in each direction through the week.</p><p /> <p> </p></ins><ins class="ministerial">The ITT for the future franchise requires bidders to provide a materially similar number of train services along the Durham Coast line each day of the week.</ins></p><p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-06-08T13:08:06.627Z","2015-06-17T14:36:24.243Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347728/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347728/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347728/answer","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347728/answer/previousversion/2943","Biography information for Andrew Jones","27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-01","Railway Stations: Horden","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the expected delivery date is for the completion of Horden Railway Station.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","584"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347729","Home Office","false","2015-06-05","<p>Communications data is fundamental to investigating crime, safeguarding national security and protecting the public. The use of these powers is subject to stringent safeguards and is regulated by the Regulation of Investigatory Powers Act 2000 (RIPA). The Interception of Communications Commissioner provides reports to the Prime Minister, which are published and laid in Parliament. These reports include statistics on the use of communications data powers by the police and other public authorities. The Commissioner’s report for 2014, which was published on 12 March 2015 (HC1113), includes a statistical breakdown, by police force, of the use of communications data powers and a breakdown of applications for communications data by statutory purpose. Beyond this, the Home Office does not collect statistics on public authority use of communications data. The recently updated Acquisition and Disclosure of Communications Data Code of Practice revised and enhanced the statistical obligations placed on public authorities. This includes reporting the purpose and (where relevant) crime type of each item of communications data included within every notice or authorisation.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2015-06-05T14:18:23.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347729/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347729/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347729/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-01","Police: Surveillance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many requests were made by the police for access to communications data relating to investigations into (a) drug offences, (b) people trafficking, (c) fraud, (d) other organised crime, (e) pornography and paedophile offences and (f) other offences in the most recent year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for John Spellar","Warley","John Spellar","593"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347730","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-04","<p>Work has now begun on the 2015 National Security Strategy and Strategic Defence and Security Review. The Review will build on the 2010 Review and will be informed by a refreshed National Security Risk Assessment. This work is led by the Cabinet Office in close consultation with relevant Departments including the Ministry of Defence.</p><p> </p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2015-06-04T16:32:57.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347730/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347730/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347730/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-06-01","Strategic Defence and Security Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what progress his Department has made on developing the next Strategic Defence and Security Review.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","594"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347731","Cabinet Office","false","2015-06-04","<p>Work has now begun on the 2015 National Security Strategy and Strategic Defence and Security Review. We expect the Review to report towards the end of the year.</p><p> </p>","West Dorset","Mr Oliver Letwin",,"2015-06-04T07:20:53.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347731/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Letwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347731/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347731/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-06-01","National Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what progress the Government has made on developing the next National Security Strategy; and when he expects that Strategy to be completed.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","595"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347732","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-08","<p>The Consumer Rights Act 2015, contains provisions for an independent statutory review of the consumer protection measures in the secondary ticketing market. It will be independently led and it will be presented to Parliament within a year of commencement.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-06-08T12:00:42.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347732/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347732/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347732/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-01","Tickets: Sales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps he is taking to monitor the effect of the secondary ticketing market on the cost of attending major sporting events.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","561"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347733","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-08","I have regular discussions with the EU Commissioners on a range of matters. The UK wants the EU to create an open, flexible digital single market with a regulatory framework that reflects the dynamic nature of the digital economy.","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-06-08T14:23:17.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347733/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347733/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347733/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-01","Digital Technology: EU Internal Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what recent representations his Department has made to the European Commission on its Digital Single Market proposals.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","562"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347734","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-08","The Mobile Infrastructure Project has completed the build of four masts, which are now live. These masts are located in North Yorkshire, Devon, Dorset and Somerset. The Department has spent £5,561,241.80 on the project.","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-06-08T14:27:38.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347734/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347734/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347734/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-01","Aerials: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many masts have been built by the Mobile Infrastructure Project; and how much his Department has spent on that project.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","563"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347735","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-04","<p>The Statement of Commitment was published on 12 March 2015 as part of the Government’s response to the consultation on ‘Tackling Partial Not-Spots in Mobile Coverage’. This is available online at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/412618/Government_Response_FINAL__1_.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/412618/Government_Response_FINAL__1_.pdf</a></p><blockquote><p> </p></blockquote>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-06-04T12:20:44.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347735/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347735/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347735/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-01","Mobile Phones","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will publish the Statement of Commitment signed with the mobile network operators in December 2014.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","564"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347736","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-08","<p>The charges laid by the Department of Justice of the United States of America relate to allegations of wrongdoing by FIFA officials in the USA. Should any further information come to light of FIFA related bribery in the United Kingdom, the case could be investigated and prosecuted in the UK.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-06-08T14:13:39.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347736/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347736/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347736/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-01","FIFA: Corruption","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps he is taking to investigate whether any bribery related to the FIFA allegations took place within the UK's jurisdiction.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","565"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347737","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-09","<p>I have already held preliminary discussions with the Executive Chairman of the Premier League on this subject. We will continue to discuss the PL's funding intentions, and together we will work in partnership to ensure funding for grassroots football remains strong. The Premier League is a global success and it is vital that this pinnacle of domestic competition is supportive of the National Game.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","567","2015-06-09T10:38:10.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347737/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347737/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347737/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-01","Football: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps he is taking to ensure the Premier League meets its commitment to fund grassroots sport.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","566"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347738","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-09","<p>I have already held preliminary discussions with the Executive Chairman of the Premier League on this subject. We will continue to discuss the PL's funding intentions, and together we will work in partnership to ensure funding for grassroots football remains strong. The Premier League is a global success and it is vital that this pinnacle of domestic competition is supportive of the National Game.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","566","2015-06-09T10:38:10.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347738/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347738/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347738/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-01","Football","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions he has had with Richard Scudamore about the Premier League's contribution to grassroots sport.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","567"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347739","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-05","<p>My Right Hon. Friend the Secretary of State is currently considering a range of options for reviewing the BBC's Royal Charter and will make an announcement in due course.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","526 ; 527 ; 528 ; 569","2015-06-05T09:03:33.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347739/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347739/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347739/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-01","BBC: Royal Charters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will set up an independent review panel for the BBC Charter Renewal.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","568"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347740","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-05","<p>My Right Hon. Friend the Secretary of State is currently considering a range of options for reviewing the BBC's Royal Charter and will make an announcement in due course.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","526 ; 527 ; 528 ; 568","2015-06-05T09:03:33.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347740/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347740/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347740/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-01","BBC: Royal Charters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will take steps to ensure that the Charter Renewal process is conducted on a cross-party basis.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","569"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347741","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-08","<p>The National Lottery etc. Act 1993 sets out clearly the four good causes that the lottery supports and the precise proportions of funding which each of the 12 Lottery distribution bodies receive. Government requires each distributor to make their guidance on how to apply for grant funding, and their policies for the appraisal of applications, widely available to the public, ensuring their decisions are open and transparent.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-06-08T14:38:54.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347741/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347741/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347741/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-01","National Lottery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what plans he has to make the allocation of funding by the National Lottery more open and transparent.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","570"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347742","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-08","<p>(a) Ofcom's Infrastructure Report 2014 <a href="http://stakeholders.ofcom.org.uk/market-data-research/market-data/infrastructure/infrastructure-2014/" target="_blank">http://stakeholders.ofcom.org.uk/market-data-research/market-data/infrastructure/infrastructure-2014</a>/ suggested that in June 2014 about 78% of UK premises had access to NGA services and about 75% had access to superfast services at 30Mbit/s or above. That figure is now likely to be above 80%.</p><p> </p><p>(b) Ofcom's UK fixed-line broadband performance report <a href="http://stakeholders.ofcom.org.uk/market-data-research/other/telecoms-research/broadband-speeds/broadband-speeds-november2014/" target="_blank">http://stakeholders.ofcom.org.uk/market-data-research/other/telecoms-research/broadband-speeds/broadband-speeds-november2014/</a> stated that 32% of UK residential broadband connections had a headline speed of ‘up to’ 30Mbit/s or higher in November 2014. Not all residential premises take any fixed broadband service.</p><p> </p><p>DCMS is not responsible for statistics on the numbers of UK residential and non-residential premises, but for modelling purposes uses a total figure of about 29 million.</p><p> </p><p>The DCMS Broadband Performance Indicators <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/broadband-performance-indicators" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/broadband-performance-indicators</a> stated that 2,411,395 premises had a superfast broadband service (above 24 Mbit/s download) made available by the end of March 2015 as a result of BDUK-supported projects. With further rollout since March, that figure will now exceed 2.5 million.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-06-08T14:54:09.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347742/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347742/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347742/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-01","Broadband: Business Premises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what proportion of premises (a) has access to and (b) is using superfast broadband; what the total number of premises is; and what proportion of that total has been provided with access to superfast broadband under the Government's rollout programme.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","611"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347743","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-09","<p>According to the information provided by Ofcom, none of the motorways and 3% of A and B roads are in complete not-spots and do not have any 2G mobile coverage. No data is available for the coverage on the rail networks but the Department for Transport is in the process of estimating mobile coverage on the rail network.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-06-09T12:25:43.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347743/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347743/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347743/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-01","Mobile Phones: Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate he has made of the proportion of the (a) major road network and (b) rail network that is a complete not-spot.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","612"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347744","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-04","<p>The procurement of the A400M aircraft remains on track to meet both its Key User Requirement and capability milestones on time, including Initial Operating Capacity in late 2015, subject to any delay resulting from the recent tragic accident involving the loss of a pre-delivery aircraft in Spain.</p><p>The programme is continually reviewed by the Senior Responsible Owner through regular Programme Boards and is subject to independent review including the Office of Government Commerce and the Major Project Review.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2015-06-04T16:02:41.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347744/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347744/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347744/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-06-01","Future Large Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what recent assessment he has made of the efficacy of the procurement of the A400M.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","552"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347745","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-04","<p>With reference to the answer I gave on 10 February 2015 to Question 222966 our desktop research has identified some further static library closures that have taken place between 7 May 2010 and 8 May 2015. Our estimate is that up to 100 static libraries have closed during this period. The DCMS does not collect information on the number of volunteer-run libraries.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-06-04T13:21:36.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347745/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347745/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347745/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-01","Public Libraries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many libraries (a) closed and (b) switched to being run by volunteers between 2010 and 2015.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","613"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347746","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-04","<p>Current desktop research indicates that up to 800 public libraries do not currently have Wi-Fi. On 18 March it was announced, as part of the Budget 2015, that £7.4m is being made available to help all public libraries to install WiFi. This programme will be run via Arts Council England who aim to launch the scheme in July.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-06-04T12:26:41.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347746/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347746/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347746/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-01","Public Libraries: WiFi","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many public libraries do not have free wifi; by what date he plans that all public libraries will have access to free wifi; and what the cost to his Department will be of providing all remaining libraries with free wifi.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","614"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347747","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-04","<p>The Museums, Libraries and Archives Council is effectively liquidated and will end as a legal entity in due course.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-06-04T12:22:41.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347747/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347747/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347747/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-01","Museums, Libraries and Archives Council","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, when the liquidation of the Museums, Libraries and Archives Council will be complete.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","615"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347748","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-09","<p>The Department for Culture, Media and Sport is committed to working closely with the Department for Communities and Local Government on sports and cultural facilities. Sport England works with a wide range of local authorities, providing expert advice and funding to sustain and increase the number of people playing sport regularly. We invest in local authority facilities projects through Sport England's range of funding programmes, such as its Improvement Fund and the Strategic Facilities Fund to make sure that facilities are modern, accessible and in the right places to have the most impact. Sport England has provided expert advice to over 80 local authorities helping them to plan their facilities better and maximise their resources.</p><p> </p><p>Local Government is the biggest public investor in arts and culture in England. Funding decisions using money generated through Council Tax and council budgets should be made at a local level and local authorities should recognise the huge benefits that investing in culture can bring, and many already do. Our City of Culture campaign celebrates local authorities which are championing culture and increasing access to the arts. Arts Council England works with local authorities to promote the impact that culture can have.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-06-09T12:40:18.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347748/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347748/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347748/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-01","Leisure: Facilities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what recent discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government on local authority funding for sports and cultural facilities.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","616"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347749","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-09","<p>We are working closely with industry stakeholders and other government departments in order to build up the framework for the consultation as set out in the Conservative manifesto. Discussions around practical arrangements are underway and we will be consulting in due course.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-06-09T11:20:37.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347749/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347749/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347749/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-01","Non-domestic Rates: Local Press","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, when he plans to consult on business rate relief for local newspapers.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","617"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347750","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-04","<p>The Government is considering its approach to delivering this commitment, and will share its plans in due course. Helping parents to protect their children from inappropriate and harmful content online remains a top priority for the Government. Work will continue on the measures implemented under the previous administration, these include easy to use parental control filters in the home.</p><p> </p><p><br>Ministers will engage with the UK Council for Child Internet Safety (UKCCIS) and other key stakeholders as this policy is developed.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","619","2015-06-04T15:40:15.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347750/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347750/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347750/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-01","Internet: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps he is taking to introduce age-restriction controls for websites.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","618"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347751","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-04","<p>The Government is considering its approach to delivering this commitment, and will share its plans in due course. Helping parents to protect their children from inappropriate and harmful content online remains a top priority for the Government. Work will continue on the measures implemented under the previous administration, these include easy to use parental control filters in the home.</p><p> </p><p><br>Ministers will engage with the UK Council for Child Internet Safety (UKCCIS) and other key stakeholders as this policy is developed.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","618","2015-06-04T15:40:15.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347751/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347751/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347751/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-01","Internet: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will introduce an independent regulator for website age-restriction controls in 2015.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","619"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347752","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-09","<p>The information is not available in the format that has been requested. According to Ofcom's 2014 Infrastructure Report 0.3% of premises (outdoor coverage) and 2% (indoor coverage) in the UK are in complete not-spots and have no 2G mobile voice coverage. The last report was published in December 2014 and can be found on the Ofcom website here:<a href="http://stakeholders.ofcom.org.uk/binaries/research/infrastructure/2014/infrastructure-14.pdf" target="_blank">http://stakeholders.ofcom.org.uk/binaries/research/infrastructure/2014/infrastructure-14.pdf</a></p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-06-09T12:44:08.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347752/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347752/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347752/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-01","Mobile Phones: Business Premises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many premises are in complete not-spots.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","620"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347753","Department of Health","false","2015-06-04","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 1 June 2015 to Question <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2015-05-27/119/" target="_blank">119</a>.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-06-04T14:35:06.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347753/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347753/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347753/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-01","King George Hospital Redbridge: Accident and Emergency Departments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what factors he took into account in deciding the timing of the announcement of the closure of accident and emergency services at King George Hospital.","false","Biography information for Wes Streeting","Ilford North","Wes Streeting","558"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347754","Department of Health","false","2015-06-04","<p>The previous Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Health, the hon. Member for Central Suffolk and North Ipswich (Dr Daniel Poulter), wrote to Simon Stevens, Chief Executive of NHS England, further to his meeting of 18 March 2015 with the Isle of Wight Clinical Commissioning Group (CCG), on 24 March 2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Minister asked that NHS England officials continue to work with the CCG to try and resolve the issues they raised, as the allocation of funding to CCGs now rests with NHS England, rather than the Department.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>NHS England has confirmed that their allocations working group is continuing to look at the CCG funding formula to ensure it accurately reflects the true cost of service provision for all areas of the country.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-06-04T13:52:45.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347754/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347754/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347754/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-01","Department of Health: Isle of Wight Clinical Commissioning Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department has taken pursuant to the meeting between the Isle of Wight Clinical Commissioning Group and the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Care Quality on 18 March 2015.","false","Biography information for Mr Andrew Turner","Isle of Wight","Mr Andrew Turner","643"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347755","Department of Health","false","2015-06-08","<p>The following hospitals were contracted NHS England providers of stereotactic radiotherapy and stereotactic radiosurgery (SRS) in 2013-14:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>- Addenbrookes Hospital, Cambridge;</p><p> </p><p>- Bupa Cromwell, London;</p><p> </p><p>- Derriford Hospital, Plymouth;</p><p> </p><p>- Mount Vernon Hospital, Middlesex;</p><p> </p><p>- Nova Healthcare/Leeds Teaching Hospitals;</p><p> </p><p>- Sheffield Teaching Hospitals;</p><p> </p><p>- Royal Preston Hospital, Lancashire;</p><p> </p><p>- Salford Royal Hospital, Salford/The Christie, Manchester;</p><p> </p><p>- St Bartholomew Hospital, London;</p><p> </p><p>- Thornbury Gamma Knife® Centre, Sheffield;</p><p> </p><p>- The Walton Centre, Liverpool/Clatterbridge Centre for Oncology, Wirral;</p><p> </p><p>- University Hospital Birmingham; and</p><p> </p><p>- University Hospital Bristol.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In early 2013-14, during the transition period associated with setting up the new commissioning arrangements, NHS England paid for SRS activity from two non-contracted providers: Queens Square Radiotherapy Centre Ltd and the Thornbury Radiosurgery Centre Ltd. However, during 2013 the Thornbury Centre became a contracted provider.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-06-08T11:08:16.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347755/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347755/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347755/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-01","Brain Tumours: Radiotherapy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, which hospitals in England have used stereotactic radiosurgery (SRS) to treat both benign and malignant tumours of the brain; which of those hospitals have contracts with NHS England to deliver SRS; and which non-contracted hospitals have received payment from NHS England for delivering SRS since 1 April 2013.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","634"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347756","Department of Health","false","2015-06-09","<p>NHS England undertook a service review and needs assessment during 2014, with appropriate public consultation, which concluded that a procurement process was required to ensure that patients are able to access high quality sustainable stereotactic radiosurgery and stereotactic radiotherapy services. The consultation report is due to be published shortly, which will also describe the next steps to further improve these services.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In line with other similar public consultation exercises, NHS England is due to publish a consultation report outlining the key themes of the consultation findings on its website.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-06-09T12:16:05.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347756/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347756/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347756/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-01","Radiotherapy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when NHS England will publish the results of its review of stereotactic radiosurgery; and for what reasons NHS England is not publishing all submissions to that review.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","635"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347757","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-08","<p>The construction of a new station at Horden is being promoted by Durham County Council and funded from the North East Local Enterprise Partnership Growth Deal. To date, no approval has been sought from the Secretary of State for its opening. The Department would expect the sponsors to work with the future Northern franchisee to develop a deliverable plan.</p><br /><p>The Invitation to Tender for the northern rail franchise, published in February 2015, confirmed that we would be asking bidders to replace the Pacer trains and introduce 120 new-build vehicles by January 2020. This is part of our transformation of rail travel in the north and a step in the creation of a northern powerhouse for the UK economy.</p><br /><p>The Government established Transport for the North (TfN) in October 2014 to formalise cooperation on transport issues in the North. The aim is for TfN to speak with one voice to Government on the transport priorities for the whole of the North. The Department is working closely with TfN and Rail North to develop and prioritise the rail options so that the first tranche is ready for consideration as part of the Government’s Rail Investment Strategy for the next rail investment period (CP6, 2019 – 2024).</p><br /><p /><p /><p>Northern Rail provides an hourly service in each direction between Newcastle and Middlesbrough throughout the day with some additional trains at peak times with some through trains serving Hexham and Nunthorpe. Northern improved the Sunday service frequency between Newcastle and Middlesbrough in May 2015 so trains now run every hour in each direction through the week.</p><p /><p>The ITT for the future franchise requires bidders to provide a materially similar number of train services along the Durham Coast line each day of the week.</p><br /> <br /> <br />","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-06-08T13:08:06.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347757/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347757/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347757/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-01","Railways: Durham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the timescale is for the withdrawal of pacer trains from rail services in East Durham.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","636"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347758","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-08","<p>The construction of a new station at Horden is being promoted by Durham County Council and funded from the North East Local Enterprise Partnership Growth Deal. To date, no approval has been sought from the Secretary of State for its opening. The Department would expect the sponsors to work with the future Northern franchisee to develop a deliverable plan.</p><br /><p>The Invitation to Tender for the northern rail franchise, published in February 2015, confirmed that we would be asking bidders to replace the Pacer trains and introduce 120 new-build vehicles by January 2020. This is part of our transformation of rail travel in the north and a step in the creation of a northern powerhouse for the UK economy.</p><br /><p>The Government established Transport for the North (TfN) in October 2014 to formalise cooperation on transport issues in the North. The aim is for TfN to speak with one voice to Government on the transport priorities for the whole of the North. The Department is working closely with TfN and Rail North to develop and prioritise the rail options so that the first tranche is ready for consideration as part of the Government’s Rail Investment Strategy for the next rail investment period (CP6, 2019 – 2024).</p><br /><p /><p>Northern Rail provides an hourly service in each direction between Newcastle and Middlesbrough throughout the day with some additional trains at peak times with some through trains serving Hexham and Nunthorpe. Northern improved the Sunday service frequency between Newcastle and Middlesbrough in May 2015 so trains now run every hour in each direction through the week.</p><p /><p>The ITT for the future franchise requires bidders to provide a materially similar number of train services along the Durham Coast line each day of the week.</p><br /> <br />","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-06-08T13:08:06.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347758/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347758/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347758/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-01","Railways: Durham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what level of investment his Department plans to make in rail services in East Durham over the next five years.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","637"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347759","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-08","<p>A joint US-UK report on technical co-operation on nuclear arms control was issued during a co-sponsored event on 11 May 2015 during the Review Conference of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty in New York. The report was published by the US on the US Department of Energy National Nuclear Security Administration website on 12 May 2015. A copy of the report can be found through the following link:</p><p>http://nnsa.energy.gov/sites/default/files/Joint_USUK_Report_FINAL.PDF</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2015-06-08T15:34:57.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347759/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347759/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347759/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-06-01","USA: Arms Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what reports have been prepared in the last 12 months on joint US-UK technical co-operation on nuclear arms control; and what circulation has been arranged for each such report.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","533"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347760","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-09","<p>No UK-US authentication workshops have been held in the UK since 2000 under the auspices of the 1958 US-UK Mutual Defense Agreement (MDA); two such meetings have been held in the US, one in March 2009 and the other in June 2014. British experts from the Atomic Weapons Establishment (AWE) participated in each workshop but their names are being withheld to protect Personal Information. A summary of the two workshops was recently presented on page 21 and 22 of the Joint US-UK Report on Technical Cooperation for Arms Control that was placed on the US National Nuclear Security Administration website on 12 May 2015. The summary can be found through the following link:</p><p>http://nnsa.energy.gov/sites/default/files/Joint_USUK_Report_FINAL.PDF</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2015-06-09T15:21:17.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347760/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347760/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347760/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-06-01","USA: Arms Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many UK-US authentication workshops have been held since 2000 in the (a) UK and (b) US under the auspices of the 1958 US-UK Mutual Defense Agreement on atomic energy matters; which British experts participated in each such workshop; and what public version reports have been published on each such workshop.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","534"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347761","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-09","<p>The Portal Monitor for Arms Control project is part of an agreed three year programme for arms control verification research, agreed between the Ministry of Defence (MOD) and the Atomic Weapons Establishment (AWE), and as such is subject to quarterly project progress and six monthly programme reviews. The project is proceeding to plan and meeting its objectives.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2015-06-09T15:20:38.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347761/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347761/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347761/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-06-01","USA: Arms Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what recent assessment he has made of the purposes, progress and funding of the joint UK-US Portal to Monitor Arms Control.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","535"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347762","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-08","<p>The Atomic Weapons Establishment received one briefing on the Controlled Intrusiveness Verification Technology (CIVET) from Brookhaven National Laboratories on 16 April 2007 in the US. This briefing was part of the ongoing technical co-operation for arms control between the US and UK to develop and evaluate methodologies and technologies to verify potential nuclear weapon treaties.</p><p> </p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2015-06-08T15:07:02.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347762/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347762/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347762/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-06-01","USA: Arms Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what information the Atomic Weapons Establishment has received from Brookhaven National Laboratory under the 1958 US-UK Mutual Defense Agreement on atomic energy matters on the Controlled Intrusiveness Verification Technology  measurement system since January 2007.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","536"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347763","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-04","<p /> <p>Details of all contracts with a value of £10,000 or over are published on Contractfinder as part of the Government’s transparency agenda.</p><p> </p><p>The information requested can be found at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk</a></p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-06-04T14:53:48.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347763/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347763/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347763/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-01","Welfare to Work: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what organisation his Department has awarded contracts or sub contracts to for the provision of welfare to work programmes in Scotland in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for John McNally","Falkirk","John McNally","548"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347764","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-04","<p>Since 2011, we have advised British nationals against all travel to Yemen. Our travel advice has included information on the current situation in Yemen, as well as of the support that can be provided in neighbouring countries. We continue to work with international partners to resolve the current crisis in Yemen and bring political stability to the country. Given the current situation in Yemen, I have not discussed this issue with the Government of Yemen since the beginning of the recent crisis.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-06-04T08:56:38.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347764/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347764/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347764/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-01","Yemen: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his counterpart in Yemen on the safety of British citizens in that country.","false","Biography information for Dame Louise Ellman","Liverpool, Riverside","Mrs Louise Ellman","549"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347765","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-08","<p>The then-Minister of State for the Home Office, Lynne Featherstone, visited Burma in January, in her role as UK Champion for Tackling Violence Against Women. She raised this issue with senior members of the Burmese government, including Ministers of the President’s Office, U Soe Thane and U Aung Min, and also with Deputy Foreign Minister U Thant Kyaw. <br><br>In our efforts to promote UNSCR 1325 (on Women, Peace and Security) in Burma, in addition to high-level lobbying, the UK has encouraged women’s full participation in the peace process, supported the drafting of forthcoming legislation on violence against women, and funded work to increase women’s participation in the electoral process. We have supported access to justice for the survivors of sexual violence. As one of the largest humanitarian donors to Kachin and Rakhine states, we have funded the coordination of activities to prevent violence against women.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2015-06-08T11:31:31.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347765/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347765/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347765/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-01","Burma: Sexual Offences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions his Department has had with the government of Burma regarding implementation of the Declaration on Preventing Sexual Violence in the last six months; and at what levels these discussions took place.","false","Biography information for Ms Diane Abbott","Hackney North and Stoke Newington","Ms Diane Abbott","583"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347766","Home Office","false","2015-06-03","<p>The Home Office provided funding to forces totalling £3.5 million in 2013, and £1.4 million in 2014 for policing the badger culls. The Department was reimbursed in full by DEFRA.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-06-03T16:47:42.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347766/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347766/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347766/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-01","Bovine Tuberculosis: Disease Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the cost is of policing the badger cull.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","591"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347767","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-08","<p>The number of badgers culled in 2014 was 341 in Somerset and 274 in Gloucestershire.</p><p>The costs for 2014 are still being collated and will be published in due course.</p><p>Bovine TB threatens the future of our beef and dairy industries and is estimated to cost the taxpayer £1 billion over the next 10 years. This is why we will continue to pursue our comprehensive strategy to eradicate TB in England by 2038.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-06-08T11:02:25.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347767/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347767/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347767/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-01","Bovine Tuberculosis: Disease Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many badgers have been culled; and what the cost to the public purse is of the badger cull.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","592"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347768","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-04","<p>There are a number of different reports and figures available on the number of British nationals living abroad and EU nationals living in the UK. These will vary depending on source, methodology and the point in time to which the figures relate. The figure which the Government believes is most accurate is from the World Bank’s “Estimates of Migrant Stocks in 2010” as updated by the UN Department for Social and Economic Affairs in 2013: http://www.un.org/en/development/desa/population/migration/data/estimates2/estimatesorigin.shtml</p><p>This report estimates that there were approximately 5.2 million British born migrants living overseas, of which approximately 1.3 million were in other EU countries. The same report estimated that there were 2.7 million EU born migrants resident in the UK. We do not have any figures distinguishing between British citizens living overseas for more or less than 15 years.</p><p> </p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2015-06-04T12:15:22.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347768/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347768/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347768/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-01","Referendums: Voting Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, with reference to page 60 of background briefing notes to the Queen's Speech 2015, what estimate he has made of the number of (a) British citizens living overseas for more than 15 years in the (i) EU and (ii) rest of the world and (b) EU citizens resident in the UK who will not be eligible to vote in the upcoming European Union referendum.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","553"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347769","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-04","<p>The Department has not received a report from Mr Noble relating to the Mozes community energy co-operative. But I understand that he was able to suggest to Mozes ways in which they could considerably reduce the life-time maintenance cost for their solar panels compared to the figure that they had originally estimated.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-06-04T08:11:12.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347769/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347769/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347769/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-01","MOZES","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, whether her Department has received a report from Ray Noble relating to the Mozes community energy co-operative.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","554"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347770","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-06-09","<p>The Government has serious reservations about this paper. It is based on a model that was not built to assess trade policy. It does not directly model trade flows or the gains from trade.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-06-09T13:41:27.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347770/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347770/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347770/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-06-01","Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will make an assessment of the working paper by Jeronim Capaldo on the Trans-Atlantic Trade and Investment Partnership, entitled European Disintegration, Unemployment and Instability.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","622"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347771","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-06-08","<p>The Government supports the Commission’s research. The UK adopted a similar approach when commissioning research for the potential impact on the UK. We also support the additional work that is underway for the Commission such as the Sustainability Impact Assessment. Whilst the trade models used by the Commission, ourselves and others have their limitations they are generally considered to be the most robust tools to examine the economic effects of trade agreements.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-06-08T13:27:48.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347771/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347771/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347771/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-06-01","Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment his Department has made of research commissioned by the European Commission into the economic effect of the Trans-Atlantic Trade and Investment Partnership.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","623"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347772","Attorney General","false","2015-06-04","<p>The Serious Fraud Office (SFO) has been aware of allegations relating to FIFA for some time and has kept the situation under active review. It would not be appropriate to go into the details of those allegations.<br><br>For the SFO to open an investigation, the Director must be satisfied that there are reasonable grounds to suspect serious or complex fraud within the UK's criminal jurisdiction.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland","627","2015-06-04T12:01:01.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347772/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347772/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347772/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2015-06-01","FIFA","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, whether criminal investigations are being carried out to determine whether UK financial institutions have been used to carry out illegal transactions related to FIFA.","false","Biography information for Clive Efford","Eltham","Clive Efford","626"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347773","Attorney General","false","2015-06-08","<p>The Serious Fraud Office engages regularly with its overseas counterparts to discuss issues of mutual interest, but it is not appropriate to comment on such casework discussions as might take place.</p><p> </p><p>It is not the practice for the Law Officers to comment upon live investigations, or to confirm or deny that Ministerial discussions about particular cases have taken place.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2015-06-08T12:56:44.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347773/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347773/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347773/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2015-06-01","FIFA: Corruption","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what discussions (a) Ministers in his Department and (b) the Serious Fraud Office have had with (i) the Swiss authorities and (ii) the US Justice Department about the investigation of fraud, racketeering and money laundering at FIFA.","false","Biography information for Clive Efford","Eltham","Clive Efford","625"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347774","Attorney General","false","2015-06-04","<p>The Serious Fraud Office (SFO) has been aware of allegations relating to FIFA for some time and has kept the situation under active review. It would not be appropriate to go into the details of those allegations.<br><br>For the SFO to open an investigation, the Director must be satisfied that there are reasonable grounds to suspect serious or complex fraud within the UK's criminal jurisdiction.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland","626","2015-06-04T12:01:02.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347774/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347774/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347774/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2015-06-01","FIFA","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, when the Serious Fraud Office first became aware that UK financial institutions may have been used to carry out illegal transactions relating to FIFA; what action was taken; and when he was first made aware of this possibility.","false","Biography information for Clive Efford","Eltham","Clive Efford","627"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347775","Department of Health","false","2015-06-09","<p>The Care Quality Commission (CQC) is the independent regulator of health and adult social care providers in England. The CQC is responsible for developing and consulting on its methodology for assessing whether providers are meeting the levels of safety and quality, including the decisions of when to publish inspection reports.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>The CQC has provided the following information:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The CQC Business Plan for 2015/16 sets out Key Performance Indicators (KPIs) to be used to monitor progress and to improve reporting to its Board and to the public. These KPIs include an aim to publish inspection reports within 50 days of an inspection. This timeframe has been extended to 65 days for hospitals so as to accommodate the extensive nature of the post-inspection process, although this is not included in the Business Plan as it is exclusive to the hospitals directorate.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Since the introduction of the new approach inspections in 2014, CQC has continued to refine the process around the publication of inspection reports. Processes have been developed to reduce the numbers of checks applied to each report as staff have become more familiar with the new methodology. There has been increased training and support for staff to fully embed the new inspection methodology and extensive inspector recruitment to fill staff vacancies. Reports are also subject to factual accuracy checks and rigorously quality assured prior to publication.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Other processes put in place by CQC to improve timely publication of reports include:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>- The establishment of quality action groups to address any performance issues.</p><p> </p><p>- Provision of initial feedback to providers at the conclusion of a planned inspection with the initiation of any required enforcement action shortly afterwards. This ensures that any action can be taken by the provider without having to wait for the final report to be published.</p><p> </p><p>- Acceleration in the production of urgent reports for services identified as higher risk straight to National Panel for a final decision prior to publication.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The quality of the inspection and the report is CQC’s key priority and CQC will continue to refine processes where necessary to ensure continued improvements in the timeliness of the inspection report publication.</p><p> </p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-06-09T11:42:19.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347775/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347775/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347775/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-01","Health Services: Inspections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he plans to take to ensure that the Care Quality Commission publishes more of its inspection reports on time.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","633"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347776","Department of Health","false","2015-06-09","<p>NHS England will be writing to clinical commissioning groups clarifying their responsibilities in respect of financial controls for agency spend which are due to be implemented from 1 July as set out in the letter from the Department of Health, a copy of which has been attached.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government is clear that the current rate of spending is not supporting the best positive outcome for patients. The Secretary of State has announced a comprehensive package of measures to address the problem including:</p><p> </p><p>- setting a maximum hourly rate for doctors and nurses;</p><p> </p><p>- banning the use of agencies that are not approved;</p><p> </p><p>- putting a cap on total agency staff spending for each National Health Service trust in financial difficulty; and</p><p> </p><p>- requiring specific approval for any consultancy contracts over £50,000.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Following the Francis[1] report many trusts increased their spend on temporary staffing to meet safe staffing levels. The Department expects the NHS to have a strong grip on its finances, and manage contract and agency staffing spend responsibly through effective and efficient workforce planning and management.</p><p> </p><br /><p>[1] <a href="http://www.midstaffspublicinquiry.com/" target="_blank">http://www.midstaffspublicinquiry.com</a></p><p> </p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-06-09T12:20:16.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347776/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347776/answer","DH letter of financial responsibilities.pdf","DH letter of financial responsibilities.pdf","DH letter - finanical controls for agency spend","DH letter - finanical controls for agency spend","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347776/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-01","NHS: Temporary Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans NHS England has to reduce the cost of agency staff to the NHS in England.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","632"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347777","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-05","<p>The Treasury ensures up to date, proportionate and effective regulation of banks and appoints independent supervisors such as the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA). This protects the integrity and stability of the financial system, making it a hostile environment for illicit finances, and supports law enforcement agencies in the investigation of criminal and terrorist financing.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The FCA is responsible for ensuring compliance of financial institutions with their anti-money laundering requirements. The FCA is operationally independent from Government and carries out its functions within the framework of statutory objectives and duties agreed by Parliament.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The FCA is discussing with banks whether the FIFA episode has highlighted weaknesses in their AML systems and controls.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Serious Fraud Office is the UK agency responsible for investigating and prosecuting the most serious cases of fraud, bribery and corruption. The SFO engages regularly with its overseas counterparts, and will assist overseas investigations as appropriate.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>It would not be right or appropriate for ministers to intervene in regulatory or criminal investigations.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-06-05T13:28:09.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347777/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347777/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347777/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-01","FIFA","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions (a) Ministers in his Department and (b) the Financial Services Authority have had with the (i) Swiss authorities and (ii) US administration's Justice Department on the investigation of fraud, racketeering and money laundering at FIFA.","false","Biography information for Clive Efford","Eltham","Clive Efford","640"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347778","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-04","<p>The UK has a comprehensive anti-money laundering (AML) and counter financing of terrorism regime‎ and we are committed to ensuring our financial system is a hostile environment for illicit finances.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Treasury is responsible for appointing AML supervisors, including the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA). The FCA is responsible for ensuring compliance of financial institutions with their AML requirements.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The FCA is operationally independent from Government and carries out its functions within the framework of statutory objectives and duties agreed by Parliament.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The FCA is discussing with banks whether the FIFA episode has highlighted weaknesses in their AML systems and controls.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-06-04T14:41:02.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347778/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347778/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347778/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-01","FIFA","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he is taking to discover whether UK financial institutions have been used to carry out illegal transactions related to FIFA.","false","Biography information for Clive Efford","Eltham","Clive Efford","641"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347779","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-04","<p>This is an operational matter for the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), who are operationally independent from Government.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The question has been passed on to the FCA. The FCA will reply directly to the honourable member by letter. A copy of the letter will be placed in the Library of the House</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-06-04T15:04:22.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347779/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347779/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347779/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-01","FIFA","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when the Financial Services Authority was informed of the possibility of UK financial institutions being used to carry out illegal transactions related to FIFA; what steps the Authority took to investigate; and when he was informed about that possibility.","false","Biography information for Clive Efford","Eltham","Clive Efford","642"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347780","Department for Education","false","2015-06-04","<p>Guidance and an application form are available on GOV.UK for all maintained schools that are considering applying to convert to academy status - <a href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/convert-to-an-academy-information-for-schools" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/guidance/convert-to-an-academy-information-for-schools</a>.</p><p>It is for schools to ensure that they have complied with relevant requirements at the point they make their application. We are exploring if there is a need to revise Regulation 46 of the School Governance (Federations) (England) Regulations 2012 and whether additional guidance is needed to support federations of schools wishing to convert. The Department does not hold data on federated schools that have already changed their status and are now open as academies. There are currently 30 federated schools with an approved academy order. These schools will open as academies in due course, subject to them conducting a consultation, and satisfying the Department that they have completed the necessary legal checks and processes.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","646 ; 647 ; 649","2015-06-04T15:50:49.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347780/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347780/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347780/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-01","Academies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment she has made of comments by a spokesman from her Department in Schools Week of 29 May 2015 that there is a technicality which needs resolving in the process of applying for an Academy Order on behalf of a federated school; and if she will revise Regulation 46 of the School Governance (Federations) (England) Regulations 2012.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","648"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347781","Department for Education","false","2015-06-04","<p>Guidance and an application form are available on GOV.UK for all maintained schools that are considering applying to convert to academy status - <a href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/convert-to-an-academy-information-for-schools" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/guidance/convert-to-an-academy-information-for-schools</a>.</p><p>It is for schools to ensure that they have complied with relevant requirements at the point they make their application. We are exploring if there is a need to revise Regulation 46 of the School Governance (Federations) (England) Regulations 2012 and whether additional guidance is needed to support federations of schools wishing to convert. The Department does not hold data on federated schools that have already changed their status and are now open as academies. There are currently 30 federated schools with an approved academy order. These schools will open as academies in due course, subject to them conducting a consultation, and satisfying the Department that they have completed the necessary legal checks and processes.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","646 ; 647 ; 648","2015-06-04T15:50:49.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347781/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347781/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347781/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-01","Academies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many Academy Orders made on behalf of a federated school have been made on or after 1 September 2012; and how many such applications (a) she has approved and (b) have an Academy Agreement in place.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","649"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347782","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-04","<p /> <p>The information for those in employment is only available for Housing Benefit (HB) recipients who do not receive: Income Support; Jobseeker’s Allowance (Income-Based); Employment and Support Allowance (Income-Based); or Pension Credit (Guarantee Credit).</p><p> </p><p>The information that shows detailed statistics to answer parts (a), (b), and (c) and those in work for HB recipients whose claim is not passported, by local authority, can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk</a></p><p> </p><p>Guidance on how to extract the information required can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started---SuperWEB2.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started---SuperWEB2.html</a></p><p> </p><p>Information on those households containing someone registered as disabled is not readily available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-06-04T15:29:56.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347782/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347782/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347782/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-01","Housing Benefit: Southwark","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many of the following households in the London Borough of Southwark with (a) dependent children, (b) a single person, (c) pensioners, (d) one or more people employed and (e) a disabled member are claiming housing benefit.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","644"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347783","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-04","<p>The Government introduced the EU Referendum Bill to the House of Commons on 28 May 2015. In the Bill, the franchise is based on the UK Parliamentary franchise with the addition of Members of the House of Lords and Commonwealth citizens in Gibraltar. The Government has no plans to lower the voting age.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2015-06-04T12:12:36.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347783/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347783/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347783/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-01","UK Membership of EU: Referendums","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if the Government will bring forward proposals to allow 16 and 17 year olds to vote in any referendum on EU membership.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","645"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347784","Department for Education","false","2015-06-04","<p>Guidance and an application form are available on GOV.UK for all maintained schools that are considering applying to convert to academy status - <a href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/convert-to-an-academy-information-for-schools" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/guidance/convert-to-an-academy-information-for-schools</a>.</p><p>It is for schools to ensure that they have complied with relevant requirements at the point they make their application. We are exploring if there is a need to revise Regulation 46 of the School Governance (Federations) (England) Regulations 2012 and whether additional guidance is needed to support federations of schools wishing to convert. The Department does not hold data on federated schools that have already changed their status and are now open as academies. There are currently 30 federated schools with an approved academy order. These schools will open as academies in due course, subject to them conducting a consultation, and satisfying the Department that they have completed the necessary legal checks and processes.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","647 ; 648 ; 649","2015-06-04T15:50:45.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347784/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347784/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347784/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-01","Academies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what information is sought from the applicant for an Academy Order for a federated school to ensure that it complies with Regulation 46 of the School Governance (Federations) (England) Regulations 2012.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","646"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347785","Department for Education","false","2015-06-04","<p>Guidance and an application form are available on GOV.UK for all maintained schools that are considering applying to convert to academy status - <a href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/convert-to-an-academy-information-for-schools" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/guidance/convert-to-an-academy-information-for-schools</a>.</p><p>It is for schools to ensure that they have complied with relevant requirements at the point they make their application. We are exploring if there is a need to revise Regulation 46 of the School Governance (Federations) (England) Regulations 2012 and whether additional guidance is needed to support federations of schools wishing to convert. The Department does not hold data on federated schools that have already changed their status and are now open as academies. There are currently 30 federated schools with an approved academy order. These schools will open as academies in due course, subject to them conducting a consultation, and satisfying the Department that they have completed the necessary legal checks and processes.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","646 ; 648 ; 649","2015-06-04T15:50:49.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347785/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347785/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347785/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-01","Academies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will place in the Library her Department's guidance on the requirements for governors making an application for an Academy Order on behalf of a federated school.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","647"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347786","Department of Health","false","2015-06-04","<p>We have no plans to introduce a sugar tax.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-06-04T15:02:18.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347786/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347786/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347786/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-01","Sugar: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to the speech at the Hay Festival by the Minister for Life Sciences on 21 May 2015, what plans he has to introduce a sugar tax.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","673"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347787","Department of Health","false","2015-06-04","<p>Information about the proportion of the mental health budget spent on forensic psychiatry is not collected centrally by the Department or NHS England.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The commissioning of a range of services to meet the needs of patients on the forensic psychiatric care pathway is the responsibility of NHS England and clinical commissioning groups.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-06-04T13:45:43.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347787/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347787/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347787/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-01","Psychiatry: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what proportion of the mental health budget has been spent on forensic psychiatry in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","674"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347788","Department of Health","false","2015-06-04","<p>The data requested is published in the Health and Social Care Information Centre’s annual ‘Hospital Episode Statistics, Admitted patient care – England’ report, which are available here:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.hscic.gov.uk/searchcatalogue?q=title%3A%22Hospital+Episode+Statistics%2C+Admitted+patient+care+-+England%22&amp;area=&amp;size=10&amp;sort=Relevance" target="_blank">http://www.hscic.gov.uk/searchcatalogue?q=title%3A%22Hospital+Episode+Statistics%2C+Admitted+patient+care+-+England%22&amp;area=&amp;size=10&amp;sort=Relevance</a></p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-06-04T15:10:11.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347788/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347788/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347788/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-01","Heroin: Overdoses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many hospital admissions were related to heroin overdoses in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","675"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347789","Department of Health","false","2015-06-04","<p>The Care Quality Commission (CQC) is the independent regulator of health and adult social care providers in England and has a key responsibility in the overall assurance of safety and quality of health and adult social care services. The CQC provides assurance that health and social care services provide people with safe, effective, compassionate high-quality care and encourage care services to improve. The CQC monitor, inspect and regulate services against meet fundamental standards of quality and safety and the CQC publish what it finds to help people choose care.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The CQC impact assessment on changes to the way they regulate and inspect services, published in September 2014, sets out the estimated costs and benefits of its new inspection model. In its Business Plan 2015-16, the CQC describes how it will continue to improve its effectiveness, and be a regulator that supports changes in health and social care. It is for the trusts to respond to CQC inspections, including when poor quality care is highlighted.</p><p> </p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-06-04T14:18:52.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347789/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347789/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347789/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-01","Care Quality Commission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the indirect cost to the NHS of the Care Quality Commission.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","676"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347790","Department of Health","false","2015-06-04","<p>National Health Service spend on agency and contract staff for 2013/14 is £3.34 billion[1].</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Following the Francis[2] report many trusts increased their spend on temporary staffing to meet safe staffing levels. The Department expects trusts to have a strong grip on their finances, and manage their contract and agency staffing spend (including use of locums) responsibly through effective and efficient workforce planning and management and to minimise temporary staffing costs in future years.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>The Government is clear that the current rate of spending is not supporting the best positive outcome for patients. The Secretary of State has announced a comprehensive package of measures to address the problem including:</p><p> </p><p>- setting a maximum hourly rate for doctors and nurses;</p><p> </p><p>- banning the use of agencies that are not approved;</p><p> </p><p>- putting a cap on total agency staff spending for each NHS trust in financial difficulty; and</p><p> </p><p>- requiring specific approval for any expensive consultancy contracts over £50,000.</p><p> </p><br /><p>[1] The 2014/15 figures reflect data collected from NHS trusts and foundation trusts as part of the Q4 data collection which is unpublished and unaudited. Whilst this data would not ordinarily be provided as part of a Parliamentary Question contribution, it has been included within this response as both Monitor and NHS Trust Development Authority have separately released data relating to temporary agency staff spend. It should be noted that their figures vary slightly from those included above. These figures may also be subject to revision as part of the 2014/15 final audited accounts production, and should therefore not be used once the final published Department of Health Annual Report and Accounts.</p><p> </p><p>[2] http://www.midstaffspublicinquiry.com/</p><p> </p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-06-04T14:33:38.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347790/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347790/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347790/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-01","NHS: Temporary Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of how much the NHS spends on agency and contract staff.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","677"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348450","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-04","<p>The Football League have made some significant steps forward over the past few years, particularly on issues like financial sustainability of their clubs. However, the events of this last week have shown us the importance of the highest standards of governance, of independence and of transparency. This is what I will continue to ask of all our sports bodies in the UK and the football authorities in this country are no different.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-06-04T12:16:59.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348450/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348450/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348450/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-01","Football","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what recent assessment his Department has made of the structure and governance of the Football League.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","900113"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348451","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-04","This Government continues to recognise the important place that brass bands have in British culture and their local communities. Before the end of the last Parliament, the Treasury confirmed that the new orchestra tax relief will be available to the full range of orchestras, including large brass bands. Orchestra tax relief will be available from April 2016.","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-06-04T12:31:59.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348451/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348451/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348451/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-01","Brass Bands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps he is taking to promote and support brass bands.","false","Biography information for Jason McCartney","Colne Valley","Jason McCartney","900111"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348452","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-04","<p>My Right Hon. Friend the Secretary of State shares a commitment with his counterpart in the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills to supporting the creative industries, and the two Departments regularly discuss issues of concern to the sector. National Minimum Wage underpins wage levels for those at work and applies equally in the creative sector as elsewhere. Creative SkillSet has published guidelines and a toolkit for employers to promote best practice and legal responsibilities for work placements in the sector.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-06-04T12:31:14.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348452/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348452/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348452/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-01","Arts: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what recent discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills on trends in the number of low-paid and unpaid jobs in the entertainment industry.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","900107"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348453","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-04","<p>The National Lottery etc. Act 1993 sets out clearly the four good causes that the lottery supports and the precise proportions of funding which each of the 12 Lottery distribution bodies receive. Government requires each distributor to make their guidance on how to apply for grant funding, and their policies for the appraisal of applications, widely available to the public, ensuring their decisions are open and transparent.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-06-04T12:18:58.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348453/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348453/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348453/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-01","National Lottery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what plans he has to make the allocation of National Lottery funding more open and transparent.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","900105"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348454","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-04","<p>New legislation came into force to improve player protections on FOBTs in April, and the law was also changed to require planning applications to be submitted to local authorities for new betting shops. Government measures on FOBTs are very new, but we are working with the Gambling Commission and industry to ensure they are effectively evaluated.</p><p>We are also pushing the industry to do more on social responsibility, including self-exclusion pilots that are currently underway in Chatham and Medway. This is the first multi-operator scheme of its kind.</p><p>I will be meeting with the Gambling Commission, Association for British Bookmakers and the Campaign for Fairer Gambling next week to discuss FOBTs and related issues.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-06-04T15:35:27.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348454/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348454/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348454/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-01","Gaming Machines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of the efficacy of current legislation on fixed-odds betting terminals; and if he will bring forward proposals for local authorities to determine locally the provision of such gaming machines.","false","Biography information for Graham P Jones","Hyndburn","Graham Jones","900110"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348455","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-04","<p>More than 2.5 million additional homes and businesses now have access to superfast broadband as a result of the Government’s intervention and 40,000 more are gaining access every week.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-06-04T12:15:34.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348455/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348455/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348455/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-01","Broadband: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what progress he has made on ensuring that the superfast broadband rollout programme reaches the most rural areas of the UK.","false","Biography information for Peter Heaton-Jones","North Devon","Peter Heaton-Jones","900109"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347395","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-08","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) constantly monitors call handling performance and assesses its quality. In 2014/15, our advisers achieved a score of 97.1% for correctness of transaction, against a 95% target.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>HMRC also carries out a quarterly customer survey to determine how well we are performing against certain criteria. The results are published quarterly on GOV.UK:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/business-plan-indicators" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/business-plan-indicators</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-06-08T14:44:08.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347395/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347395/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347395/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-05-29","Revenue and Customs: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent assessment he has made of the efficiency of call-handling by HM Revenue and Customs.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","512"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347396","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-03","<p>The Chancellor of the Exchequer is actively engaged, as a full member of the National Security Council, in the Strategic Defence and Security Review.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2015-06-03T16:09:05.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347396/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347396/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347396/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-05-29","Strategic Defence and Security Review: Departmental Coordination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what discussions he has had with the Chancellor of the Exchequer on the forthcoming Strategic Defence and Security Review.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","495"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347397","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-03","<p>The Devolved Administrations will be consulted on the Strategic Defence and Security Review.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2015-06-03T16:11:11.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347397/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347397/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347397/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-05-29","Strategic Defence and Security Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what discussions he has had with the devolved administrations on the forthcoming Strategic Defence and Security Review.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","496"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347398","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-04","<p>In the Queen's Speech on 27 May 2015, the Government made clear its intention to conduct a full Strategic Defence and Security Review. Led by the Cabinet Office, the Government will consult with the academic and think tank communities, defence industry, members of Parliament and the public to inform our decision-making</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2015-06-04T16:22:15.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347398/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347398/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347398/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-05-29","Strategic Defence and Security Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what plans he has to consult (a) the public, (b) the defence industry and (c) academics on the forthcoming Strategic Defence and Security Review.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","494"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347399","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-03","<p>The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs and the Secretary of State for International Development are actively engaged, as full members of the National Security Council, in the Strategic Defence and Security Review.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2015-06-03T16:10:42.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347399/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347399/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347399/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-05-29","Strategic Defence and Security Review: Departmental Coordination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for (a) Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs and (b) International Development on the forthcoming Strategic Defence and Security Review.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","497"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347400","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-03","<p>The Ministry of Defence and HM Treasury hold regular discussions concerning Defence spending.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2015-06-03T16:09:36.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347400/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347400/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347400/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-05-29","Ministry of Defence: Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what recent discussions he has had with the Chancellor of the Exchequer on Ministry of Defence spending in 2015-16 and future years.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","507"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347401","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-04","<p><strong> </strong>The current Survey and Inspection Transformation Programme is reviewing and assessing the numbers of survey and inspection staff required to deliver the survey and inspection regime in future years. The business case is due to be complete in the Autumn of 2015.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-06-04T12:46:19.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347401/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347401/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347401/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-05-29","Maritime and Coastguard Agency: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent assessment he has made of the expected availability of qualified maritime (a) surveyors and (b) inspectors over the next five years.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","454"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347402","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-04","<p>The average age of the 125 Marine Surveyors employed by the Maritime and Coastguard Agency is 52 years and 4 months.</p><p> </p><p>There are 10 surveyors who are 65 years or over and another 32 will reach that age within the next five years.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-06-04T12:52:40.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347402/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347402/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347402/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-05-29","Maritime and Coastguard Agency: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the average age is of (a) inspectors and (b) surveyors employed in the Maritime and Coastguard Agency; and how many staff employed in each position will reach 65 years of age within the next five years.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","455"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347403","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-04","<p>The Maritime and Coastguard Agency’s (MCA) Survey and Inspection Transformation Programme will review the terms and conditions for Marine Surveyors and will consider the appropriateness of the current employment contract arrangements.</p><p> </p><p>The MCA did not pay any consultancy fees in drawing up these contracts. As the contract applies to all Department for Transport (DfT) staff, both DfT and the MCA consulted the Trade Unions on the new contract. The Unions balloted their members and accepted the contract. This became effective from August 2012.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-06-04T13:03:25.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347403/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347403/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347403/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-05-29","Maritime and Coastguard Agency: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of the new employment contract for maritime surveyors employed by the Maritime and Coastguard Agency (MCA); what consultancy fees were paid by the MCA in drawing up that contract; what consultation was undertaken with MCA staff on that contract; and when that contract will come into effect.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","456"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347404","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-04","<p>Officials at the Department for Transport (DfT) designed and negotiated new terms and conditions of employment for all DfT staff, including those for Marine Surveyors. An offer was presented to the Trade Unions and they balloted their members and accepted the offer.</p><p> </p><p>The provision of out of hours working was and remains on a voluntary and non-contractual basis. The Maritime and Coastguard Agency’s (MCA) Survey and Inspection Transformation Programme will review the terms and conditions for Marine Surveyors and will consider the appropriateness of the current employment contract arrangements.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-06-04T13:14:36.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347404/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347404/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347404/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-05-29","Maritime and Coastguard Agency: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the role of his Department was in the design of the new employment contract for maritime surveyors and inspectors employed by the Maritime and Coastguard Agency; and what impact assessment his Department has made of the provision to end the contractual commitment to provide out of hours contact.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","457"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347405","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-04","<p>The Maritime and Coastguard Agency’s (MCA) targets for ship survey and inspection work for the last 10 years, and its performance against these targets is shown below:</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="3"><p><strong>Port State Control (PSC) Inspections</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Target</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Performance</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2005</p></td><td><p>1614</p></td><td><p>1768</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006</p></td><td><p>1630</p></td><td><p>1661</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007</p></td><td><p>1626</p></td><td><p>1639</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p>In 2008 the measure changed to inspecting at least 25% of foreign ships visiting the UK</p></td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><p>2008</p></td><td><p>25%</p></td><td><p>Achieved – (1660)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009</p></td><td><p>25%</p></td><td><p>Achieved – (1684)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>25%</p></td><td><p>Achieved – (1666)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>25%</p></td><td><p>Achieved – (1459)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>25%</p></td><td><p>Achieved – (1452)</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p>In 2013 the measure changed to a fair shared commitment that is set by the</p><p>European Maritime Safety Agency (EMSA)</p></td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>1535</p></td><td><p>Met – (1384)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>1177</p></td><td><p>Met – (1279)</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>EMSA does not recognise Gibraltar as a separate flag-State, so taking Gibraltar’s performance into account the UK has met its PSC target for the past 10 years.There are no published targets for UK vessel inspections or survey and certification work that is performed annually by MCA surveyors. However, the two tables below show the number of survey and inspections that have been completed in the last 10 years.</p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><p><strong>Survey &amp; Certification</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2005</p></td><td><p>4028</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006</p></td><td><p>3968</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007</p></td><td><p>3900</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008</p></td><td><p>3869</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009</p></td><td><p>3664</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>3747</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>4165</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>3817</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>3633</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>3426</p></td></tr></tbody></table><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><p><strong>UK Vessel Inspections</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2005</p></td><td><p>5352</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006</p></td><td><p>4818</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007</p></td><td><p>5350</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008</p></td><td><p>4485</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009</p></td><td><p>5941</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>4500</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>4315</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>3879</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>3730</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>3446</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-06-04T13:27:32.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347405/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347405/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347405/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-05-29","Maritime and Coastguard Agency: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the Maritime and Coastguard Agency's (MCA) targets were for ship (a) survey and (b) inspection work in each of the last 10 years; and what the MCA's performance was against each such target in each of those years.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","458"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347406","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-04","<p>Inspection work is not performed by classification societies.</p><p> </p><p>The information about the proportion of survey work performed by classification societies is not recorded.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-06-04T13:41:58.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347406/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347406/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347406/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-05-29","Maritime and Coastguard Agency: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what proportion of the Maritime and Coastguard Agency's ship (a) survey and (b) inspection work was completed by classification societies in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","459"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347407","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-04","<p>The Maritime and Coastguard Agency has not made any payments to any classification societies in any of the last 10 years.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-06-04T13:47:44.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347407/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347407/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347407/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-05-29","Maritime and Coastguard Agency: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much the Maritime and Coastguard Agency paid to classification societies in each of the last 10 years; and for what categories of work these payments were made in each of those years.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","460"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347408","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-04","<p>The Maritime and Coastguard Agency has not historically recorded vacancy rates for specific professions within the Agency.</p><p> </p><p>The current vacancy rate for Marine Surveyors is 15.0%</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-06-04T13:54:32.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347408/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347408/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347408/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-05-29","Maritime and Coastguard Agency: Vacancies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the vacancy rate was for maritime (a) surveyors and (b) inspectors in the Maritime and Coastguard Agency in (i) the most recent period for which figures are available and (ii) each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","482"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347409","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-04","<p>The number of Marine Surveyors that have left and joined the Maritime and Coastguard Agency in each of the last 10 years is shown below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><br><p>Financial Year</p></td><td><p>Leavers</p></td><td><p>Starters</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2005-2006</p></td><td><p>9</p></td><td><p>6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006-2007</p></td><td><p>10</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007-2008</p></td><td><p>11</p></td><td><p>8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008-2009</p></td><td><p>7</p></td><td><p>11</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009-2010</p></td><td><p>12</p></td><td><p>11</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-2011</p></td><td><p>8</p></td><td><p>6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-2012</p></td><td><p>14</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-2013</p></td><td><p>8</p></td><td><p>6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-2014</p></td><td><p>11</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-2015</p></td><td><p>11</p></td><td><p>7</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-06-04T13:59:29.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347409/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347409/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347409/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-05-29","Maritime and Coastguard Agency: Labour Turnover","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many maritime (a) surveyors and (b) inspectors have (i) left and (ii) joined the Maritime and Coastguard Agency in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","483"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347410","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-08","<p>Before a decision can be made to make an investment in field trials, we need to be confident that we have an effective DIVA test (a TB test to differentiate infected from vaccinated animals). The work we have already done shows that the blood test DIVA is unlikely to be good enough, in that it will yield too many false positive results leading to slaughter of too many uninfected cattle. So we are now investing in the development of a more promising skin test DIVA.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-06-08T15:08:55.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347410/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347410/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347410/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-05-29","Bovine Tuberculosis: Vaccination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what progress her Department has made on commencing field trials for a cattle vaccine for bovine TB.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","471"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347411","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-04","<p>To date, no other EU member States have expressed interest in developing a TB vaccine for cattle. But we are working with officials and businesses in both New Zealand and the USA in our quest to identify, through research, an effective DIVA test (a TB test to differentiate infected from vaccinated animals), which is a critical element of any programme which would involve BCG vaccination of cattle.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-06-04T11:04:12.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347411/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347411/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347411/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-05-29","Bovine Tuberculosis: Vaccination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what discussions her Department has held with other EU member states in which bovine TB occurs on establishing joint research on a TB vaccine for cattle.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","472"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347412","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-08","<p>In the comprehensive TB Strategy we commit to pursuing options to license a cattle vaccine by 2023, or sooner if possible, but the hurdles remain very high. The 10 years indicative timeline set out by the Commission was an indication of the timescale for allowing free movement of vaccinated cattle in the EU. It may be possible for vaccination to be used in the UK before then but we are still some way from that, given the need to develop an effective DIVA test (a TB test to differentiate infected from vaccinated animals) and, if we are successful in that, what would then inevitably be lengthy, wide-scale and expensive field trials.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-06-08T16:31:55.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347412/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347412/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347412/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-05-29","Bovine Tuberculosis: Vaccination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will publish the most recent update of the tentative timeline for possible use of a vaccine against bovine TB in the EU as set out by the EU Commissioners in January 2013.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","473"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347413","Cabinet Office","false","2015-06-04","<p>The Government considers tackling electoral fraud as a high priority and believes that more needs to be done to safeguard the integrity of elections.</p><p>The Electoral Commission has been developing proposals for a scheme to require voters in polling stations to provide identification before they can be issued with ballot papers. The Government will consider these proposals in due course.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose",,"2015-06-04T15:35:04.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347413/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347413/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347413/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-05-29","Elections: Proof of Identity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to the Answer of 21 May 2012, Official Report, column 483W, on voter identification, whether the Government plans to bring forward legislative proposals during the course of the current Parliament to require voters to produce photographic identification at polling stations.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","516"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347414","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-08","<p>Seal conservation is a devolved issue so I can only respond with respect to England. Approximately 85% of the UK seal population is in Scotland and the Scottish government have their own legislation concerning the protection of seals.</p><p>Seals in England are primarily protected by the Conservation of Seals Act 1970. Under this Act, it is an offence to take or kill common and grey seals out of season or to use certain methods to kill or take, unless permitted to do so by a licence issued under the Act.</p><p>No licences have been issued for the culling of seals in England in the last five years.</p><p>The Act also allows the Secretary of State to provide year round protection in any specified area. Such a ‘Conservation Order’ currently protects grey and common seals on the east coast of England. Given the distribution of seal populations in England, this Order has the net effect of providing year round protection for almost all common seals and the majority of grey seals in England.</p><p>The Law Commission has carried out a review of wildlife law and will publish its final report this summer.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-06-08T13:09:34.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347414/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347414/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347414/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-05-29","Seals: Conservation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will review the effectiveness and adequacy of current legislation on the protection and conservation of seals.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","475"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347415","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-03","<p>The Government provides public and Lottery funding to Arts Council England who allocates this to arts organisations and regional museums across England. The Arts Council uses a range of criteria to support a fair distribution of this public funding. The Arts Council are committed to increasing Lottery arts investment outside of London from 70 per cent to 75 per cent by the end of 2018 and recently launched a new £35.2 million fund 'Ambition for Excellence' to support arts production, talent development and leadership outside London.</p><p>DCMS encourages partnership working between national and regional museums across England through object loans, touring exhibitions and partnership galleries. In addition, a number of national museums are either based in or have branches across England, such as National Museums Liverpool and the Royal Armouries.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-06-03T08:04:23.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347415/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347415/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347415/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-05-29","Arts: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps his Department plans to take to ensure fair and equal distribution of public funding for museums and the arts across the UK.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","520"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347416","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-03","<p>We will publish a full Impact Assessment in due course.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-06-03T16:42:03.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347416/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347416/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347416/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-05-29","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the number of households in each (a) region, (b) constituent part of the UK and (c) constituency that would be affected by a household benefit cap of £23,000.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","508"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347417","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-08","<p>Seal conservation is a devolved issue so I can only respond with respect to England. Approximately 85% of the UK seal population is in Scotland and the Scottish government have their own legislation concerning the protection of seals.</p><p>No licences to cull seals, under the Seals Act 1970, have been issued in England since 2010.</p><p>A ‘Conservation Order’ currently protects grey and common seals on the east coast of England. Given the distribution of seal populations in England, this Order has the net effect of providing year round protection for almost all common seals and the majority of grey seals in England.</p><p>Fishermen are permitted to kill or take, without the need for a licence, to protect their fishing equipment or fish therein if the seal is in the vicinity of the equipment at that time.</p><p>The Government has not made an assessment of the number of seals that may have been killed off the English coast.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-06-08T11:37:32.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347417/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347417/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347417/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-05-29","Seals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate she has made of the number of seals killed by the British fishing industry in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Susan Elan Jones","Clwyd South","Susan Elan Jones","478"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347418","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-08","<p>Seal conservation is a devolved issue so I can only respond with respect to England. Approximately 85% of the UK seal population is in Scotland and the Scottish government have their own legislation concerning the protection of seals.</p><p>Seals in England are primarily protected by the Conservation of Seals Act 1970. Under this Act, it is an offence to take or kill common and grey seals out of season or to use certain methods to kill or take, unless permitted to do so by a licence issued under the Act.</p><p>Before an individual is granted a licence for the lethal control of any animal, including seals, they must first demonstrate that less severe alternatives have been exhausted or shown to be unworkable. Consequently, the existing arrangements already help to promote the use of non-lethal control.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-06-08T11:38:44.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347418/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347418/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347418/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-05-29","Seals: Conservation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will take steps to encourage the use of non-lethal seal deterrents on the coast.","false","Biography information for Susan Elan Jones","Clwyd South","Susan Elan Jones","479"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347419","Home Office","false","2015-06-02","<p>Under the provisions of the Private Security Industry Act 2001, the Security Industry Authority (SIA) is responsible for licensing individuals who operate in designated sectors of the private security industry. The SIA has procedures in place to ensure that licences are not issued fraudulently and that private security operatives are 'fit and proper' persons who are properly trained and qualified to do their job. Before issuing a licence, the SIA undertakes checks to verify an individual’s identity, their age, whether they have completed the required level of training and whether they have a criminal record. Since 2012, the SIA has taken action against more than 1,300 licence holders who have used fraudulent qualifications to gain an SIA licence.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-06-02T16:08:12.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347419/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347419/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347419/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-05-29","Security Guards: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps she is taking to tackle Security Industry Authority licences being issued fraudulently.","false","Biography information for Kwasi  Kwarteng","Spelthorne","Kwasi Kwarteng","474"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347420","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-03","<p>We are on track with our plans for the national roll out of Universal Credit. Universal Credit is already available in over 40% of Jobcentres and will be present in all by Spring 2016.The Department is not setting targets for numbers in receipt of Universal Credit because numbers will vary according to factors such as economic circumstances and the behavioural change of claimants.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","503","2015-06-03T15:44:20.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347420/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347420/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347420/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-05-29","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent estimate he has made of the number of people who will be claiming universal credit in April (a) 2016, (b) 2017, (c) 2018, (d) 2019 and (e) 2020.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","502"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347421","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-03","<p>We are on track with our plans for the national roll out of Universal Credit. Universal Credit is already available in over 40% of Jobcentres and will be present in all by Spring 2016.The Department is not setting targets for numbers in receipt of Universal Credit because numbers will vary according to factors such as economic circumstances and the behavioural change of claimants.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","502","2015-06-03T15:44:20.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347421/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347421/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347421/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-05-29","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent estimate he has made of the number of households with children which will be claiming universal credit in April (a) 2016, (b) 2017, (c) 2018, (d) 2019 and (e) 2020.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","503"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347422","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-03","<p /> <p>We are continuing to work with Departments to help them determine their earnings thresholds. Decisions on the provision of those benefits, including the eligibility and verification arrangements to confirm entitlement, will remain the responsibility of the Departments that own them.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-06-03T15:08:55.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347422/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347422/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347422/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-05-29","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when he plans to publish details of the earnings thresholds for universal credit that will be used to determine eligibility and entitlement to passported benefits.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","504"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347423","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-03","<p /> <p>We will publish a full impact assessment in due course.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-06-03T16:36:15.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347423/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347423/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347423/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-05-29","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the number of people residing (a) in inner London, (b) in outer London and (c) outside London who would be affected by a reduction of the benefit cap to £23,000.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","505"
